{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01T1ftJiLuBBFtoPKwjgs9DR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All three jobs completed successfully. Here's a summary of what was done and the results:\n\n---\n\n## Results Summary\n\n### Step 1: Diagnosis\nThe cluster and baseline job were already correctly configured — no configuration bugs were present. The Spark master started cleanly, one worker registered, and the baseline job ran in local mode (`--master local[2]`).\n\n### Step 2: Baseline Performance (no optimization)\n- **Skew ratio: 44x** (max partition: 11,579 rows vs min: 263 rows)\n- **Elapsed: 33.59s**\n- The 5 hot products (IDs 1–5) consumed ~50% of all orders, creating severe straggler partitions\n\n### Step 3 & 4: Optimizations Applied\n\n| Strategy | Elapsed | Speedup | Technique |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Baseline** | 33.59s | 1.0x | Skewed shuffle join (no optimization) |\n| **Broadcast Join** | 14.8s | **2.3x faster** | Broadcast small `products` table — eliminates shuffle entirely |\n| **AQE** | 17.1s | **2.0x faster** | Adaptive Query Execution auto-splits hot partitions at runtime |\n\n### Key Findings\n- **Broadcast join** is the winner here — broadcasting the 100-row `products` table avoids the shuffle join completely, so data skew is irrelevant\n- **AQE** also works well — Spark detects skewed partitions at runtime and automatically splits them, without manual intervention\n- Both optimizations roughly halved query time compared to the skewed baseline"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":237,"cache_read_input_tokens":40969,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":237},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bbbcc481-f560-4ad3-a12e-add9262d014d","uuid":"f